column12: Didgeridoo containing an inserted sound emitting device
Wind instrument with double didgeridoo shape has two mouthpieces and one combined resonant chamber
column13: A wind instrument with a double didgeridoo shape has a single box shaped resonant chamber open at the bottom and with two mouthpieces. The inside of the resonant chamber is structured to give different sounds from the two mouthpieces. The instrument can also be played by inverting and blowing into the open base.

The musical instrument I've created and designed is distinctive due to the fact it is made out of aluminium cans which are stacked on top of one another. Although the instrument looks like a souvenir item it still works and sounds like a didgeridoo when played.
Didgeridoo stand in the shape of a map of Australia.

column12: Telescopic didgeridoo consists of four elongated tubes sliding inside each other so that when not use, smallest tubes are stored within largest tube and maintained by two flat tops, one inserted at each end of largest tube
column13: Didgeridoo consists of four elongated tubes (1, 2, 3, 4) able to slide inside each other, so that when didgeridoo is not in use, three smallest tubes (1, 2, 3) can slide and be stored within largest tube (4). When in collapsed position, elongated tubes are maintained inside largest tube by two flat tops, one inserted at each end of largest tube. Rubber ring is placed at extremity of smallest tube so as to protect lips of musician when playing. Insert can be placed inside didgeridoo and slide within so as to modify tone of didgeridoo.

column12: Method of making plastic didgeridoo musical instrument involves forming plastics body which is then heated and shaped
column13: The plastic didgeridoo is made by forming a shell out of plastic and heating to allow deformation to an irregular shape. The ends are reheated to form the mouthpiece (A-D) and the trumpet (E). The mouthpiece can be covered with a mixture of plastics covered in natural wax (A) to seal the mouthpiece with the instrument.

The "Venturi Didgeridoo" or "Reverse Didgeridoo" is a musical instrument played in the manner of a didgeridoo (i.e. with an "unvoiced linguolabial trill" made by loosely vibrating or "fluttering" lips). It consists of one or more venturi chambers in which the diameter of the mouth opening (proximal end) is greater than the diameter of the opening at the distal end (in novel contrast to the construction of any other end-blown musical instrument). This tapered tube constitutes a venturi chamber in which the velocity of air is increased at the point of greatest constriction and in which internal pressure is increased at the point of greatest diameter. This unique acoustical design creates pitches that are much lower than those possible in traditional didgeridoos of equal length. A sequence of several separate venturi chambers consisting of graduated cylinder sections of diminishing diameter will result in an extremely compact, collapsing (telescoping) instrument.

A method of making a didgeridoo includes the steps of selecting two identical pieces A,B of timber, machining a longitudinal semicircular groove along a matching face of each piece, gluing the pieces together to create a centralised cylindrical hole C, and then lathing the external surfaces of the joined pieces to create a substantially cylindrical instrument. The instrument may have two external grooves D for accepting a carrying strap, and may have a mouthpiece (E, fig 4) of a rubbery consistency.

Plastic mouth piece for poly vinyl chloride didgeridoo, has rotation symmetrical part, where mouth piece is attached at discharge pipe by clamp, and diameter of discharge pipe is forty millimeter
column13: The mouth piece has a rotation symmetrical part, where the mouth piece is attached at a discharge pipe by a clamp, and the diameter of the discharge pipe is forty millimeter. The mouth piece is made of commercial poly vinyl chloride (PVC) and is manufactured by a computer numerical control lathe.

column12: Musical instrument i.e. didgeridoo, has keys placed on tubular section, where keys are arranged to be actuated by fingers of musician to quickly change air column and make instrument polytonic
column13: The instrument (10) has a tubular section (13) arranged between a mouthpiece (11) and a pavilion (12), where a hole (20) is formed in the tubular section. Seven keys (21) are placed on the tubular section, where the keys are arranged to be actuated by the fingers of a musician to quickly change an air column and make the instrument polytonic, and the keys are placed to obtain a major or minor range. A valve (23) is arranged to move between closed position and open position of the hole, where a chimney (22) surrounds the hole.

column12: Telescopic didgeridoo with octave color tone indication comprising a wooden outer tube and a metal inner tube having sound depth indicators useful in Australia
column13: A telescopic didgeridoo with octave color tone indication consisting of:(1a) an outer wooden tube and an inner metal tube, (1b) two corresponding metal tubes, (1c) two corresponding wooden tubes, (1d) a wooden outer tube and an inner tube in PVC, glass, or carbon, a construction which provides a means of obtaining any depth of sound as controlled by the length and diameter of the instrument.

column13: A didgeridoo comprising an elongate hollow body having two ends, one end being the mouthpiece and the other end being the outlet, and a didgeridoo sound-emitting device positioned at least partially within the body, the device having activation means to allow the device to be selectively activated to produce a didgeridoo sound.

column12: DIDGERIDOO CONTAINING AN INSERTED SOUND EMITTING DEVICE
Double didgeridoo made in Y-shape with two mouthpieces connected to single main body so two people can play it at same time
column13: A double didgeridoo for two players is made in a Y-shape, e.g. from a branching section of a tree about 1.25 m long overall and with two branches 40 cm long, hollowed out with a tool like a big industrial drill to make two mouthpieces (1, 2) and a single open outlet end (3). In variants the instrument can be carved from a single solid tree trunk section measuring 1.25 m long by 50 cm diameter, or it can be moulded from fibres, aluminium or other material. It can also be made with more than two mouthpieces.

column12: Didgeridoo is made of basalt fibers using fiber composite technique, where basalt fiber mats are soaked in epoxy resin and wound around core, and core is removed after hardening epoxy resin in fiber composite technique
column13: The didgeridoo is made of basalt fibers using a fiber composite technique. Basalt fiber mats are soaked in epoxy resin and wound around a core, where the core is removed after hardening the epoxy resin in the fiber composite technique.

column12: Metal didgeridoo musical instrument has body with screw on mouthpiece and flare sections having O-ring seals
column13: The metal didgeridoo musical instrument has three detachable sections. the mouthpiece (1) is cylindrical and hollow and has an external flange (7) and an inner thread (6) to receive a threaded stub on the top of the body of the instrument. the threaded joint has a sealing O-ring (8). The instrument body has bands and the lower end is threaded (9) with an O-ring (10) to receive the top of the flare (4).
